  "texts": [
    "Offensive AI, or attacks utilising AI, refers to the employment or exploitation of AI for the purpose of carrying out malicious activities, such as developing new cyberattacks or automating the exploitation of existing vulnerabilities [4].",
    "Adversarial AI, or the abuse and misuse of AI systems [10], on the other hand, refers to attacks that exploit vulnerabilities in AI systems to cause them to make incorrect predictions [11,12].",
    "This can be done by manipulating the input data to the AI system, or by poisoning the training data that the AI system was trained on [13].",
    "Table 1 summarises the key differences between defensive, offensive, and adversarial AI according to [5,6,[13][14][15][16].There is limited research on offensive and adversarial AI from a non-technical perspective, with the existing literature focusing primarily on the technological dimension of both defensive, adversarial and offensive AI.",
    "This highlights a need for more holistic research on AI in cybersecurity, considering the non-technical factors that can influence AIdriven threats."
  ],
